ificant funding is also provided by the Wellcome Trust and other charities. The Institute focuses on the translation of basic research on haematology and single gene disorders, cancer, immunology and infection, for patient benefit. Two MRC Units are based at WIMM: the MRC Human Immunology Unit (research themes include: autoimmunity; tumour immunology; immunity to and vaccination against HIV infection; molecular and cellular biology of the immune system in health and disease; and immune responses to influenza) and the MRC Molecular Haematology Unit (research programme includes the study of acquired and inherited haematological disorders, particularly thalassaemia, sickle cell disease, myelodysplasia and leukaemia; the Unit also runs a prenatal diagnosis programme for haemoglobin disorders for the UK). Aside from these Units, research groups are divided into 7 streams: neurosciences (immune-mediated and genetic ion channel disorders), molecular immunology (currently effects of HIV on cellular iron metabolism), paediatric molecular medicine (molecular basis of bacterial virulence), clinical genetics (genetic basis of neonatal congenital abnormalities), medical oncology (cell signalling and genetic stability), molecular parasitology (molecular biology of malaria parasites) and haematopoetic stem cell biology (cellular and molecular pathways of fate decisions in normal and leukaemic cells).</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2005-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>943504</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr